The '''Victoria County Station''' was a proposed [[nuclear power plant]], in [[Victoria County, Texas|Victoria County]], 13.3 miles south of [[Victoria, Texas]].{{coord|28|36|52|N|97|1|50|W|type:landmark_globe:earth_region:US-TX|display=title}}<ref name="victoria-cola">{{Cite report|date=September 2, 2008|title=Victoria County Station, Units 1 and 2 Combined License Application|url=http://pbadupws.nrc.gov/docs/ML0825/ML082540600.pdf|publisher=Exelon Generation|chapter=Environmental Description|page=2.1-1|accessdate=December 2014}}</ref> The plant, consisting of two 1535 MWe [[GE Hitachi Nuclear Energy|General-Electric-Hitachi]] [[Economic Simplified Boiling Water Reactor|economic simplified boiling water reactors]] was applied for by the [[Exelon|Exelon Nuclear Texas Holdings, LLC]] on September 2, 2008.<ref name="thomasOneill-nrc-letter">{{cite letter|first=Thomas S.|last=O'Neill|recipient=U. S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission Document Control Desk|subject=Exelon Nuclear Texas Holdings, LLC Victoria County Station, Units 1 and 2 Application for Combined Licenses for Victoria County Station NRC Project Number 761|date=September 2, 2008|url=http://pbadupws.nrc.gov/docs/ML0825/ML082540469.pdf|publisher=Exelon Generation|accessdate=December 2014}}</ref> The project was canceled in August 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.neimagazine.com/story.asp?sectionCode=132&storyCode=2062971 |title=Exelon scraps Texas reactor project |author= |date=29 August 2012 |work=Nuclear Engineering International }}</ref>
[[Exelon]] filed a [[Combined Construction and Operating License]] (COL) application for the plant on September&nbsp;3, 2008 with the [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC). In July 2009, Exelon announced that it was suspending its COL application. In March 2010, Exelon announced that it was formally withdrawing its COL application, while submitting its application for an early site permit (ESP).<ref>{{cite news | url= http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/NN-ESP_application_for_new_Texan_plant-2603105.html | title= ESP application for new Texan plant | date= 26 March 2010 | work= World Nuclear News |publisher= | accessdate= 2010-03-26 }}</ref>
On August 28, 2012, Exelon announced that it had notified the Nuclear Regulatory Commission that it was withdrawing its ESP application, which brought to an end all project activity.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/28/us-utilities-exelon-texas-idUSBRE87R0UH20120828 | title= Exelon drops Texas reactor plan, cites cheap natural gas | date= 28 August 2012 | work= Reuters|publisher= | accessdate= 2012-08-29 }}</ref>
